<div class="blurb">
<div class="header"><h1>summary</h1></div>
<div class="body">
<ul>
<li>I will grudgingly accept MSG occuring naturally in things like cheese.
What I need to know is how much MSG is being added to my food, so I can make
sure I consume a safe level.
<li>some diseases seem to come from nowhere:
 <ul>
  <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diabetes">diabetes</a> -- virus, genetic</li>
  <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_sclerosis">multiple sclerosis</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parkinson%27s_disease">Parkinson's disease</a></li>
 </ul>
<li>MSG = monosodium + glutamate</li>
<li>glutamate is one of 20 ammino acids</li>
<li>it is *possible* for msg to form during the cooking process, thus the term "no msg" is "impossible". correct term is "no added msg"</li>
<li>"<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/001126.htm">MSG Symptoms Complex</a>" is a newer name for "Chinese Restaurant Syndrome"</li>
<li>glutamate is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurotransmitter">neurotransmitter</a>, which is part of the normal function of the
body</li>
<li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Excitotoxicity">Excitotoxicity</a> -- too much glutamate</li>
<li>any restaurant is going to see MSG as one way to lower food cost</li>
<li>the body does not need to make it's own glutamic acid. it comes from food typically bound to protein</li>
<li>no chef worth their jacket would use MSG in their kitchen(s)</li>
{*<li>lots of sodium and glutamate can cause problems</li>*}
<li>sodium from table salt plus sodium from MSG = ?</li>
<li>"Glutamate excitotoxicity (sometimes called a glutamatergic storm) refers to the damage to nerve cells caused by excessive stimulation of NMDA and AMPA receptors by glutamate.” Jul 2, 2018
source: <a href="https://neurohacker.com/what-is-glutamate">What is Glutamate?</a> -- too much glutamate</li>
<li>"NMDA is an unfortunate acronym for N-methyl-D-aspartate, and this amino acid derivative is very similar to glutamate. Now glutamate is the excitatory neurotransmitter found in most synapses of the central nervous system, and pharmacologists made this analogue called NMDA to activate a sub-type of glutamate
receptors." -- source: <a href="https://dnalc.cshl.edu/view/1211-What-is-NMDA-.html">what is NMDA</a></li>
<li>"AMPA (α-amino-3-hydroxy-5-methyl-4-isoxazolepropionic acid) is a compound that is a specific agonist for the AMPA receptor, where it mimics the effects of the neurotransmitter glutamate. ... AMPA generates fast excitatory postsynaptic potentials
(EPSP)." -- source <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AMPA">wikipedia
AMPA</a></li>
<li>"In excitotoxicity, nerve cells suffer damage or death when the levels of otherwise necessary and safe neurotransmitters such as
glutamate,..." -- source <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Excitotoxicity">wikipedia Excitotoxicity</a></li>
<li>"An excitatory postsynaptic potential (EPSP) is the change in membrane voltage of a postsynaptic cell following the influx of positively charged ions into a cell (typically Na+) as a result of the activation of ligand-sensitive
channels." -- source <a href="https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-3-540-68706-1_618">Encyclopedia of Psychopharmacology (2010)</a></li>
<li>"Chronic inflammation of the pancreas can damage the cells that produce insulin which can lead to diabetes. Pancreatitis and type 2 diabetes share some of the same risk factors. Observational studies indicate that people with type 2 diabetes may have a two- to threefold increased risk of acute
pancreatitis." -- source <a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes-and-pancreas">The Connection Between Diabetes and Your Pancreas</a></li>
<li>"It refers to a group of symptoms some people experience after eating food from a Chinese restaurant. Today, it's known as MSG symptom complex. These symptoms often include headache, skin flushing, and sweating. A food additive called monosodium glutamate (MSG) is often blamed for these
symptoms." (2012) -- source <a
href="https://www.healthline.com/health/chinese-restaurant-syndrome">Chinese
Restaurant Complex and MSG Symptom Complex</a></li>
